docs.abstract: The ruling could cost public-sector unions more than a million members. But the ones who stay could make labor more powerful.
docs.snippet: The ruling could cost public-sector unions more than a million members. But the ones who stay could make labor more powerful.
docs.lead_paragraph: With the Supreme Court striking down laws that require government workers to pay union fees, one thing is clear: Most public-sector unions in more than 20 states with such laws are going to get smaller and poorer in the coming years.

headline.main: Labor Unions Will Be Smaller After Supreme Court Decision, but Maybe Not Weaker
headline.print_headline: Labor’s Likely Future: Fewer Members And More Engagement

docs.abstract: David M. Solomon, president of Goldman Sachs, is expected to be named its future chief as soon as Monday, helping him line up his own new team.
docs.snippet: David M. Solomon, president of Goldman Sachs, is expected to be named its future chief as soon as Monday, helping him line up his own new team.
docs.lead_paragraph: Goldman Sachs is expected to name its president, David M. Solomon, as its next chief executive early this week, according to people briefed on the plan. The announcement would formally establish Mr. Solomon as the successor to Lloyd C. Blankfein as one of the most powerful executives on Wall Street.

headline.main: Goldman Expected to Name David Solomon as Successor to C.E.O. Lloyd Blankfein
headline.print_headline: Goldman Expected to Formally Name Next C.E.O.

docs.abstract: The state oil company was under pressure after ConocoPhillips, which had won an arbitration ruling in a decade-long fight, seized cargoes and terminals to force compliance.
docs.snippet: The state oil company was under pressure after ConocoPhillips, which had won an arbitration ruling in a decade-long fight, seized cargoes and terminals to force compliance.
docs.lead_paragraph: HOUSTON — More than a decade ago, Venezuela seized several oil projects from the American oil company ConocoPhillips without compensation. Now, under pressure after ConocoPhillips carried out its own seizures, the Venezuelans are going to make amends.

headline.main: Venezuela Agrees to Pay $2 Billion Over Seizure of Oil Projects
headline.print_headline: Venezuela to Pay ConocoPhillips $2 Billion for Seizing Oil Projects
